The paper deals with lower bounds on the size of AC$^0$ formulas, which is a topic in computational complexity theory (cs.CC). The use of linear subspaces and their action on formulas suggests a connection to linear algebra and group theory, which are relevant to data structures (cs.DS) and logic (cs.LO). The paper also involves information theory (cs.IT) in the form of Hamming weights. Finally, the use of lower bounds and combinatorial techniques suggests a connection to discrete mathematics (cs.DM).
